#debtfreecommunity

node.text:
If all of your debts are paid in full and the accounts are closed, you'll have what's called an "indeterminable" credit score after about 6 months. Then, you'll be able to do what's called "manual underwriting" to buy a home. All that means is that the mortgage company will do what banks used to do all the time when someone bought a home. They'll actually review your finances to check out whether or not you're in a position to pay back the loan.

A mortgage is the only type of debt, I'm okay with. Just make sure that the payment is no more than 25% of your take-home pay on no more than a 15-year mortgage at a fixed rate. I want your house to be a financial blessing in your life, not a financial curse.

You CAN have financial peace. You just need to take your time and do the math to make sure things are done right.

Thanks to Dr. @johndelony for joining me on this call. 

#debtfreecommunity 
#mortgage

node.text:
There's an addictive thrill that can come with the risk on these sorts of things. Although a lot of people are having a lot of fun with this right now, it's important to not confuse a get-rich-quick scenario with an actual, proven wealth-building plan. Just because a few people won the lottery one time does NOT make it an investment strategy that you should use. If you're debt-free with a full emergency fund, and you want to use some fun/entertainment money that you've budgeted for to play around with these things, I'm not gonna get mad at you, but I don't recommend it… and I certainly don't do this myself. If you REALLY want to play around with single stocks, just make sure that no more than 10% of your net worth is tied up in them. This is to ensure that things don't go overboard to the point that it can actually impact your net worth in a negative way if and when things go south. 

Reminder: I only recommend investing in mutual funds and real estate that's paid for in full. 

#debtfreecommunity

node.text:
Great conversation with @kencoleman.

Budgeting isn't easy at first, but it's worth it. You've got to push through a few months to learn how to get your budget right. It's only when the pain of where you are exceeds the pain of making the change that you will actually decide to CHANGE. The struggle at the beginning is part of the learning process.

Push through— you'll get there. You can do this! 💪

#debtfreecommunity

node.text:
WOW. $247,000 PAID OFF! You did it! SO proud of you. 🎉

#repost @elisedds

19 months ago I decided to do something unordinary. I challenged myself to pay off my student loans and car as quickly as possible. Some people thought I was nuts, but others cheered me on until I completed this marathon, or sprint, however you choose to perceive it. This came with extreme sacrifices such as not partaking in most weekend activities, no vacations or shopping for anything other than basic necessities. This journey sucked, but it taught me a lesson in contentment, perseverance, grit and determination.

I want to thank my amazing fiancé, Nnamdi, for being the most patient and understanding person as I took on this insane journey. It all started because of one car ride home from London with you we caught an episode of @daveramsey and I was inspired to change our family tree and legacy we’ll leave behind. From that day forward, I listened to @daveramsey and @anthonyoneal on my commute home from work to remain motivated. To God all the glory! I can finally say I’M DEBT FREEEEE!!!!!!🎉

#debtfree #livelikenooneelse #freedom
#debtfreecommunity #debtfreescream

node.text:
Solid advice from my team. Remember, winning with money is about what you DO with your money, not as much about the amount you make. Every bit of progress counts! 

#repost @ramsey.solutions

We'd all love to save more money, but how do you actually start? You just gotta do it!
 
For sure, it's not easy. But you’ll only start saving money when you learn healthy money habits and let your future needs be more important than your current wants—when you make saving money a priority.
 
So let's get started! What ideas would you add to this list?

#debtfreecommunity

node.text:
Well done, you guys! 

#repost @ember.jae

After cramming our 45 month goal into 15 months, WE ARE COMPLETELY DEBT FREE, and our lives are forever changed 🤍
.
.
.
Before getting married my parents gifted us with the Dave Ramsey program and I think we would both truly agree it was the greatest gift we could have been given!
We came from extremely different money backgrounds. My family being very frugal and his not so much. We worked very hard to establish what values and core beliefs were important to the both of us, as well as, what long term goals we wanted to see in our family. The first one being getting out of debt. The borrow truly is slave to the lender and in listening to the Ramsey series we decided our main goal was to live like to one else now, so we could live and give like no one else later.
Being debt free was definitely not any easy task. We both worked lots of side jobs: door dash, substitute teaching, construction work, VIPKid, and Quick Trip were just a few on that list.
Unexpected things also happened, I was in a massive hit and run car wreck caused by an uninsured driver, our apartment flooded beyond repair during a huge winter storm, and Yosh had some crazy job changes.
Through it all, we continued to persevere and constantly assess our goals and plans. We can truly say that the Lord has been so faithful to us. He has grown us closer than we could have ever imagined and the peace that has come from taking this great step is incredible!

#debtfreecommunity
#debtfreescream
